threats.tagLine: Anthropogenic pressures on birds, habitats they rely on, and/or an entire ecosystem
threats.title: A climate-endangered species
threats.description:
• Sea level rise
  • Increased storms and king tides
  • Ocean acidification
  • Disturbance from coastal users
  • Avian predators
  • Climate change

actions.tagLine: Conservation interventions by Audubon field staff and partners as classifed by the Conservation Measures Partnership
actions.title: Monitoring productivity since 2012
actions.description:
• Monitoring and research to track the health of Black Oystercatcher populations by measuring productivity
  • Engagement to increase public awareness of oystercatchers, including signs, magnets, pamphlets, lectures, and conversations with coastal users and business owners
  • Habitat management and restoration to protect and enhance Black Oystercatcher populations and other societal benefits

objectives.description: Continue monitoring productivity along the California coast and use the data to conduct a population viability assessment
objectives.tooltip: Continue monitoring productivity along the California coast and use the data to conduct a population viability assessment

responses.tagLine: Quantifying the effectiveness of our conservation actions using scientifically-sound metrics
responses.title: California intertidal is critical for the Black Oystercatcher population
responses.description:
• Until recently little was known of its status and distribution in California
  • Over 1300 birds and over 170 nests were detected in California suggesting the species is stable in the state
  • We estimate 4000-6000 oystercatchers in California, making our state critical for the species. Productivity monitoring from 2012-2016 has found a statewide fledge success (fledged chicks per pair per year) of between 0.41-0.49.
  • Audubon Christmas Bird Count shows significant increase in winteringÂ oystercatchers between 1966 and 2017

objectives.description: Maintain 0.41 fledged chicks per pair per year

partners.tagLine: Our work is co-developed and often led by partner organizations and stakeholders
partners.title: A network of state partners
partners.description:
• Over 150 participants from coastal chapters and agencies, including the Mendocino Coast Bureau of Land Management, California Coastal National Monument, California State Parks, and Oikonos Ecosystem Knowledge. Audubon chapters include Mendocino Coast, Madrone, Golden Gate, Marin, and Monterey.
  • Funding for the program has been provided by the Marisla Foundation, the Resources Legacy Fund, the Bureau of Land Management, and private donations.
